            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-155051" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-155051" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Pretty well everyone did pay contributions to friendly societies, except the very poor indeed.  So, let&#8217;s assume that I am happy to accept that health and education are merit goods so it can be justified that they can be funded by transfer payments to the unfortunate.  The question really is, are such transfer payments best administered by a great &#8216;caste&#8217; of professional and parasitical bureaucrats at the national level or would it better to deal with the administration at local level?  All the evidence is that national central planning bureaucracies are woefully inefficient at this and often divert such subsidies to their own pet boondoggles, especially as there is zero cost to them.  Whereas if administered locally by local people paying over local taxpayers wealth I think that there is a better than even chance that the whole thing could be run much more cheaply &#8211; and in a much more democratic and decent way that the current proto-Stalinist system.</p>
</div>
        </div>

